Step 1: Define Core Entities

Start with the most important objects in a real estate project:

Developer
Project
Land
Unit
Buyer
Contractor
Payment

Step 2: Add Attributes to Each Entity

Now give details to each entity:

Entity: Developer
- developer_id
- name
- company_name

Entity: Project
- project_id
- name
- location
- total_units
- status

Entity: Land
- land_id
- area
- price
- approval_status

Entity: Unit
- unit_id
- type (2BHK, 3BHK)
- price
- status (available/sold)

Entity: Buyer
- buyer_id
- name
- contact

Entity: Payment
- payment_id
- amount
- date
- status


 Step 3: Define Relationships

This is the core of entity modeling:

Developer → owns → Project
Project → built_on → Land
Project → contains → Unit
Buyer → purchases → Unit
Buyer → makes → Payment
Contractor → builds → Project


Step 4: Add Basic Logic (Mini BAML Layer)

Now add simple rules:

IF land.approval_status != approved:
    project.status = "on hold"

IF unit.status == sold:
    assign buyer

IF payment.status != completed:
    do not confirm booking

Step 5: Visual Understanding (Simple Flow)

Think of it like this:

Developer
   ↓
Project
   ↓
Land + Contractor
   ↓
Units
   ↓
Buyer → Payment


